  pathophysiologyText: "MDD pathophysiology involves complex interactions across multiple neurobiological systems. The monoamine hypothesis (serotonin, noradrenaline, dopamine deficits) remains clinically relevant but is insufficient to explain the full picture. Contemporary models emphasise: (1) dysregulation of the HPA axis with cortisol hypersecretion and hippocampal volume reduction via glucocorticoid neurotoxicity; (2) neuroinflammatory processes with elevated IL-6, TNF-α, and CRP that impair neuroplasticity and monoamine synthesis; (3) impaired BDNF signalling and synaptic plasticity in hippocampal and prefrontal circuits; (4) glutamatergic dysfunction including reduced NMDA tone and impaired long-term potentiation; and (5) large-scale brain network dysregulation. These mechanisms co-occur in varying combinations, producing the heterogeneous clinical presentations that map onto distinct FNON phenotypes. The HPA-neuroplasticity-network framework provides the integrated biological rationale for multi-modal FNON intervention.",
